******
[2]
Date: Wed 28 May 2014
Source: blog.al.com [edited]
http://blog.al.com/wire/2014/05/legionnaires_cases_jefferson_c.html


The Jefferson County Department of Health is working on a statement to the public aimed at easing fears over the deaths of 2 people at UAB Hospital who tested positive for _Legionella_ bacteria, which cause an acute pneumonia sometimes called legionnaires' disease.

"It's not like the Ebola virus just hit Birmingham or anything like that," said Dr Mark Wilson, health officer for the county. Wilson said _Legionella_ bacteria are not all that uncommon and that they see "sporadic cases that hit several times a year."

It's also important to note that in these 2 deaths, the victims, who have not been identified, had other health problems that likely compromised their ability to fight it, Wilson said. In all 8 people were infected, all in the same hematology/oncology unit. The source is believed to be the water system specifically tied to floors 5-7 in the Women and Infant building.

UAB says it has made that water safe. The health department wants to stop fears that it may be bigger than an isolated incident, Wilson said. "It is safe to drink the city water -- that's one of the kind of fears we are trying to ease," Wilson said. The hospital is investigating to find any other patients who may have been exposed to the water in that area of the hospital.

Visitors to that area of the hospital are asked to see a doctor if they start having symptoms, Wilson said. "If someone was visiting that section and having symptoms, and was exposed to the water, then they should see a doctor and get it checked out," Wilson said. Citing confidentiality laws, UAB Hospital has declined to release the names of the patients nor the dates of their deaths except to say they occurred in "the early to mid-May range." The health department's statement will likely be released this afternoon, Wilson said.

CDC estimates that between 8000 and 18 000 people are hospitalized with legionnaires' disease in the United States each year.

[Byline: Mike Oliver]

