[The news reports above says that the legionellosis outbreak occurred in a hematology/oncology unit on the 5-7 floors of the Women and Infant building and was tied to the water system in this part of the University of Alabama (UAB) hospital. The 1st case occurred in March 2014 and no additional cases have occurred since remediation of the water system that was undertaken on 7-9 May 2014. There has been a total of 8 or 9 cases; 2 were fatal and 1 involved an immunocompromised visitor to the unit affected.

Genotyping of patient and environmental isolates has become a helpful tool to establish transmission pathways. The predominance of one genotype of _Legionella_ isolated from patient specimens would suggest transmission from a common source. Because _Legionella_ may be found in environmental samples without linkage to any cases of legionellosis, the actual causative infectious reservoir can be confirmed by matching the genotype of clinical and environmental isolates (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC86783/ and http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2730281/).

UAB Hospital is Alabama's major tertiary care center and a 908-bed modern medical complex, which serves as the teaching hospital for UAB School of Medicine. The hospital is, with 18 750 employees, the largest employer in Birmingham and the 2nd largest employer in Alabama (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UAB_Hospital). The US News & World Report has ranked several of its clinical specialty programs among the nation's best.

For a discussion of legionnaires' disease, see moderator ML's comments in prior ProMED-mail posts, such as,
Legionellosis - USA (05): (OH) fatal, retirement community 20130727.1849540 and
Legionellosis - UK: (Scotland) 20130703.1805239. - Mod.ML

